3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.3008a790-2263-4ce8-ad2a-b85a68cca0ff.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.4a1f4692-3773-4423-8a9e-ee973d3bc217.description=
Retrieve information about a virtual machine or a set of virtual machines in a datacenter or host system. Retrieve each object one at a time from an initial search query as the one used in the SQL Query operation.

Inputs\:
    host - VMware vCenter, ESX or ESXi host hostname or IP.
    user - VMware username.
    password - VMware user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    vmDatacenter - Datacenter to get virtual machines from.
    hostSystem - Host system to get virtual machines from.
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type.  Required if virtualMachine input is used.
Valid values\: "inventorypath", "name", "ip", "hostname", "uuid", "vmid"
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    getDetailed - Retrieve detailed information?
Valid Values\: true, false
    connectionTimeout -  The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A "connectionTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20
    socketTimeout -  The time to wait for data (a maximum period of inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20

Results
    returnResult - Virtual machine ID (vmid) or reason for failure.
    vmInfo - Detailed virtual machine information when getDetailed is true.  Properties in this result are pipe delimited.
    numberOfResults - Number of results from the query remaining to be retrieved.
    name - Name of the virtual machine.
    uuid - UUID of the virtual machine.
    inventoryPath - Inventory path of the virtual machine.
    dataStore - The name of the datastore where the vm configuration file (.vmx) is stored.
    vmxPath - The path to the vm configuration file (.vmx) on dataStore.
    pendingVMQuestion -The current question, if any, that is blocking the virtual machine's execution.
    questionAnswerChoices - A list of comma separated values representing the possible answers that can be used to answer the question returned by the 'pendingVMQuestion' result. 

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.  See returnResult for details.
    no more - There are no more results to retrieve.

Notes\:
1) Depending on the "host" input value, the inventory path can have one of the following formats\: 
    - If "host" is an ESX server, the inventory path will have the format\: ha-datacenter/vm/
    - If "host" is a vCenter, the inventory path will have the format\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. 
2) The inventory path is case sensitive.
3) Regarding the questions returned by the "pendingVMQuestion" result\:
    3.1) Sometimes, while performing certain changes to a virtual machine, you may be prompted in the vSphere client with a question, which will block the virtual machine and preventing the changes from taking effect until an answer is provided or until the underlying task (visible in the 'Tasks' view in the vSphere Client) fails due to time out.
    3.2) The question is related to the specified virtual machine and it can olny be obtained while the underlying task performing the changes to the virtual machine is in the running state.
3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.4c13d62a-7c58-4689-955f-00a3e06f2fdd.description=
 Apply a guest customization spec to an existing VM.

Inputs\:
    host - VMWare vCenter hostname or IP.
    user - VMWare username.
    password - VMWare user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type (inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid).
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
    customizationTemplateName - Name of the customization specification to apply to the virtual machine. The customization specification should already exist in the vCenter customization specifications manager. This is not a required input. However, if  both 'customizationTemplateName' and 'customizationSpecXml' are empty or have input, the operation will give an error message and fail. Hence, either 'customizationTemplateName' or 'customizationSpecXml' should have an input.
    customizationSpecXml - The Xml string of the customization spec to apply. This is not a required input.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Operation result message.

Notes\:
1>Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.

2>Guest customization spec can be applied only to a vm.

3>If the operation fails due to "A customization operation is pending on the vm\: ", then restart the guest of the vm before applying a different customization specification.

4>The result of the VMware/VMware Virtual Infrastructure and vSphere/Guest/Export Guest Customization Spec operation can be used to get the customizationSpecXml input value.

5>If the Microsoft Sysprep Tools for a particular windows guest operating system is not already bundled with the vCenter Server then it must be installed on the vCenter Server system. For instructions on Guest Operating System Customization Requirements see "Customizing Guest Operating Systems" on page-42 in http\://www.vmware.com/pdf/vsphere4/r41/vsp_41_vm_admin_guide.pdf



3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.4c9cc91c-9ec1-446f-b025-28586f0e8ce9.description=
This operation executes a command from the command line of a remote RAS. 
When running on Unix, you cannot determine the type of shell to be used (sh, bash, ksh, csh, etc), so make sure to include the shell in your command if you want to perform operations such as file redirection.  
Example\: sh -c "ls -lha /etc > /tmp/myfile".

When running on Windows, this command  prepends "cmd.exe /C" or "command.exe /C" to the command you specify, so there is no need to pass this information to the operation.

Inputs\:
    command - The command to execute.
    arguments - Any arguments needed for the command.
    environment - Specifies environment variables/values that need to be defined when running the command.
    path - The path to the commands executable.
    cmd_timeout - Timeout in milliseconds before the command is considered as having failed when "returnImmediately" is false.
Default value\: 100000 (100 seconds).
    returnImmediately - If "true", the operation executes the command and returns a result immediately.  It does not wait for the command to finish.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: false.

Results\:
    STDOUT - The standard output of the command.
    STDERR - The standard error output of the command.
    exitStatus - Every command returns an exit status (sometimes referred to as a return status or exit code). A successful command returns 0, while an unsuccessful one returns a non-zero value that usually can be interpreted as an error code.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.


Example\:
   This is a valid input example for executing a "ping" command from a Windows machine\:
    command\: ping
    arguments\: example.server.com

3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.50958e26-0c52-4e17-ba74-8b1a94f0a107.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex (The values are not case sensitive)
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.


3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.575bb16d-74fb-4ae3-8381-4812cabf0fe2.description=
Add a new virtual (SCSI) disk to an existing virtual machine.

Inputs\:
    host - VMWare host hostname or IP.
    user - VMWare username.
    password - VMWare user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
Default value\: 800
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type.
Valid values\: "inventorypath", "name", "ip", "hostname", "uuid", "vmid"
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
    dataStore - Datastore or datastore cluster.
Examples\: host\:dsname, mydatastore
    vmDiskSize - Size of the virtual disk to create in megabytes (MB).
    vmDiskSizeUnit - The unit for "vmDiskSize" input.
Valid values\: MB, GB
Default\: MB
    diskPath - Path on datastore to use for backing the new virtual disk. Include .vmdk suffix and do NOT include leading / . This path must not already exist on the datastore.
    diskMode - Disk persistence mode. Values for ESX 3 and later VMs\: persistent, independent_persistent, independent_nonpersistent. Valid values for pre ESX 3 VMs\: persistent, nonpersistent, undoable, append.
    thinProvision - Perform thin provisioning of the virtual disk.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    eagerZero - Specify if the thick disk type (thinProvisioning input set to false) is eager zero or lazy zeroed. Data located on eager zeroed disks is zeroed out when the virtual disk is created. It migth take longer to create disks in this format
Valid values\: "true", "false"
Default Value\: "false"
    diskWritethrough - Enable direct write to the file system.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    diskSCSINode - The SCSI Node where the disk should be attached. If the input is left empty the operation will work in auto select mode.
Examples\: "0\:0", "0\:5", "2\:1", "2\:-1", "1\:15"
    controllerType - The SCSI controller type used when creating a new controller. If the input is left empty the operation will work in auto select mode.
Valid values\: "BusLogic Parallel", "LSI Logic Parallel", "LSI Logic SAS", "VMware Paravirtual"

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Task result or operation result.
    deviceNumber - The device number of the created disk. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    allocatedSize - Size of the hard disk backing files in bytes.  If the disk is thin provisioned, this value will be lower then the provisioned size (vmDiskSize). This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    diskPath - Path to the disk on the datastore. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    dataStore - Name of the datastore that contains this disk. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    diskMode - The disk persistence mode.  Possible values\: persistent, independent_persistent, independent_nonpersistent. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    thinProvision - Hard disk is thinly provisioned.  Possible values\: true, false. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    uuid - Universally unique identifier (uuid) of the disk. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    vmDiskSize - The size of the hard disk in bytes.  If the hard disk is thinly provisioned, this is the provisioned size. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    diskSharesLevel - The vm hard disk shares level. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    diskShares - The number of shares allocated to the hard disk. The "Normal", "High" and "Low" disk shares level map to a pre-determined set of numeric values for shares. The  "Custom" disk shares level does not map to a pre-determined set of numeric values for shares. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
    parentListJS - If this disk has a delta disk backing file, this result contains a JSON array of the parent virtual disk backing files. This output will be populated only if the operation is running to success and synchronously (async false).
Example\: ["[datastore] path to\/parent virtual disk backing file.vmdk","[datastore] path to\/grandparent virtual disk backing file.vmdk"]

Notes\:
1. Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.
2. If a data cluster is provided in the "dataStore" input, the operation will apply a Storage DRS recommendation.
3. The SCSI Node from "diskSCSINode" represents "SCSI controller (bus) number"\:"Disk unit number on the controller". Valid values for SCSI controller number are\: 0,1,2,3 and for disk unit number\: 0,1,2,...,15 without 7 (reserved by WMware).
4. If the "diskSCSINode" is left empty the first empty space on an existing controller will be used or a new controller will be automatically created if a controller number is available. If the unit number is set as -1 the operation will find the first empty space on the specified controller.
5. If the "controllerType" input is left empy the operation will use the type of the first controller found on VM or the "BusLogic Parallel" if the newly created controller is the first one attached to the VM.
6. The "parentListJS" result can be used to determine the parent of a linked vm that share the same base disk storage. 
7. The "parentListJS" result will be populated with vSphere API 4.0 or greater.

3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.65c8f6b7-9566-47ae-a292-8ab46c846f7f.description=
Increases the size of a hard disk on a virtual machine.

Inputs\:
    host - VMWare host hostname or IP.
    user - VMWare username.
    password - VMWare user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
Default value\: 800
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/MyResourcePool/MyVM), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123)
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter
    diskSize - The size of the disk for a virtual machine in GB. If it is less than the current disk size, the operation will complete succesfully, but the disk size will remain unmodified.
    deviceNumber - The virtual disk number on the VM.  As an example\: "Hard disk 1" would be deviceNumber "1". This input and 'uuid' are mutually exclusive.
    uuid - Universally unique identifier (uuid) of the disk. This input and 'deviceNumber' are mutually exclusive.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Task result or operation result. Reason for error on failure.

3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.93cecdc8-40a4-43b8-8ff3-04f32ffcd0f0.description=
Modifies an existing Network Interface Card (NIC) on a virtual machine. Optional inputs with a "net" and "connect" prefix that are left empty will not be modified on the NIC.

Inputs\:
    host - VMware vCenter, ESX or ESXi host hostname or IP.
    user - VMware username.
    password - VMware user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMware Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait in seconds before the operation is considered to have failed.
Default value\: 800
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type 
Valid values\: "inventorypath", "name", "ip", "hostname", "uuid", "vmid"
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
    deviceNumber - The NIC number to modify on the VM.  As an example\: "Network Adapter 1" would have be deviceNumber "1".
Examples\: If a VM as a network adapter named "Network Adapter 1" the deviceNumber would be "1".
    netPortGroup - Name of port group to connect this NIC to.  This port group can be a legacy port group or a distributed virtual port group.
Examples\: "VM Network", "dvPortGroup"
    netNicType - Virtual network interface card type. NIC type VmxNet2 is only supported for virtual machine hardware version 4 and later.  NIC type VmxNet3 is only supported for vitual machine hardware version 7 and later.
Valid values\: "PCNet32", "E1000", "VmxNet", "VmxNet2", "VmxNet3"
    netMacAddr - MAC address to assign if netMacGeneration is set to Manual.
Value format\: Six groups of two hexadecimal digits (0-F), separated by colons (\:).
Examples\: 00\:50\:56\:94\:AB\:EF
    netMacGeneration - MAC address assignment method. 
Valid inputs\: "Manual", "Generated", "Assigned" (Assigned value is only valid when host is a vCenter server. Will assign MAC from vCenter).
    netWakeOnLan - Enable Wake On LAN for the NIC.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    connect - Connect the NIC to the network?  Only applicable when VM is powered on.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    connectAtPowerOn - Connect the NIC to the network at power on time of VM?
Valid values\: "true", "false"

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong. See returnResult for details.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Task result or operation result

Notes\:
1. Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.

3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.9d0384de-c059-436c-9508-19da8327f737.description=
Deploys a virtual machine from a template. The source is the templateName while the deploy is defined by .

Note\: cannot work across virtual datacenters

Inputs\:
    host - VMware vCenter, ESX or ESXi host hostname or IP.
    user - VMware username.
    password - VMware user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
Examples\: 443, 80
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMware Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
Default value\: 800
    templateName - Name of the template to deploy from. 
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter. If host is ESX(i) use "ha-datacenter".
    vmName - Name of new virtual machine being created.
    vmFolder - Virtual machine's inventory folder. Folder names are delimited by a forward slash "/".  This input is case sensitive.  Only supported when host is a vCenter.  For root folder, use "/".
Example\: /Hewlett Packard Enterprise/Operations Orchestration/VMs
    vmResourcePool - Resource pool for new virtual machine. Resource pool names are delimited by a forward slash "/".  For the root resource pool, specify "Resources" or a single "/".
    dataStore - Name of datastore or datastore cluster to store new virtual machine (eg. host\:dsname, mydatastore).  If not specified the same datastore of the source virtual machine will be used.
    hostSystem - Name of destination host system (ESX or ESXi) for new virtual machine as seen in the vCenter UI.  Only supported when host is a vCenter.  If not specified the same host system of the source virtual machine will be used.
    clusterName - Name of the VMWare HA or DRS cluster.  Can be specified instead of hostSystem if the desired destination ESX(i) host is in a DRS or HA cluster.
    thinProvision - Specifies whether to perform thin provisioning of the virtual disk. If empty, the disk format will be set as same format as source. If true, the disk format will be set as thin provisioned format. If false, the disk format will be set as thick format.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    customizationTemplateName - Name of the customization specification to apply while creating this clone. The customization specification should already exist in the vCenter customization specifications manager. If  both 'customizationTemplateName' and 'customizationSpecXml' have values, the flow will fail.
    customizationSpecXml - The Xml string of the customization spec.
    connectionTimeout -  The time to wait for a connection to be established, in seconds. A "connectionTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20
    socketTimeout -  The time to wait for data (a maximum period of inactivity between two consecutive data packets), in seconds. A "socketTimeout" value of '0' represents an infinite timeout.
Default value\: 0
Format\: an integer representing seconds
Examples\: 10, 20

Responses\:
    success - The flow completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Notes\:
1) The result of the VMware/VMware Virtual Infrastructure and vSphere/Guest/Export Guest Customization Spec operation can be used to get the customizationSpecXml input value.
2) Note that "socketTimeout" and "connectionTimeout" inputs do not represent the time to wait for the operation to complete. They are used when communicating with the service, to make sure that the service is up and responds to client's requests. They can be used for service diagnosis purpose.
3) The "taskTimeOut" input is only used when the task is performed in a synchronous manner ("async" is set to "false").


3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.9d1bf123-8081-4736-84f4-ed2a998cde2f.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.a140ab0e-a372-4cd4-b07d-51922c1ea1d2.description=
 Apply a guest customization spec to an existing VM.

Inputs\:
    host - VMWare vCenter hostname or IP.
    user - VMWare username.
    password - VMWare user's password.
    port - Port to connect on.
    protocol - Connection protocol.
Valid values\: "https", "http"
    closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    async - Asynchronously perform the task.
Valid values\: "true", "false"
    taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
    vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type (inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid).
    virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
    vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
    customizationTemplateName - Name of the customization specification to apply to the virtual machine. The customization specification should already exist in the vCenter customization specifications manager. This is not a required input. However, if  both 'customizationTemplateName' and 'customizationSpecXml' are empty or have input, the operation will give an error message and fail. Hence, either 'customizationTemplateName' or 'customizationSpecXml' should have an input.
    customizationSpecXml - The Xml string of the customization spec to apply. This is not a required input.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed successfully.
    failure - Something went wrong.

Returns\:
    returnResult - Operation result message.

Notes\:
1>Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.

2>Guest customization spec can be applied only to a vm.

3>If the operation fails due to "A customization operation is pending on the vm\: ", then restart the guest of the vm before applying a different customization specification.

4>The result of the VMware/VMware Virtual Infrastructure and vSphere/Guest/Export Guest Customization Spec operation can be used to get the customizationSpecXml input value.

5>If the Microsoft Sysprep Tools for a particular windows guest operating system is not already bundled with the vCenter Server then it must be installed on the vCenter Server system. For instructions on Guest Operating System Customization Requirements see "Customizing Guest Operating Systems" on page-42 in http\://www.vmware.com/pdf/vsphere4/r41/vsp_41_vm_admin_guide.pdf



3cced3a7-12b8-48b6-a2a9-82479438ab56.b4155c46-f7bc-4da5-a321-3ccdaa74a1fd.description=
Sets the memory size for a virtual machine. Virtual machine cannot be in a suspended power state.  Memory hot add is supported if enabled for the virtual machine.

Inputs\:
   host - VMWare host hostname or IP.
   user - VMWare username.
   password - VMWare user's password.
   port - Port to connect on.
   protocol - Connection protocol. Valid values\: http, https.
   closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation. Valid values\: true, false.
   async - Asynchronously perform the task. Valid values\: true, false.
   taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
   virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
   vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type. Valid values\: inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid.
   vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
   vmMemorySize - New memory size for the virtual machine in megabytes.  This number must be a multiple of 4.

Responses\:
   success - If async is true the task was successfuly queued.  If async is false the memory size for the virtual machine was successfully set.
   failure - Something went wrong.  See returnResult for details.

Returns\:
   returnResult - Task result or operation result.

Notes\:
   1. Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.
   2. Memory limits\: The maximum value for 'vmMemorySize' is based on the virtual hardware version of the virtual machine. Limits are as follows\:
      Virtual hardware 11 (vSphere 6.0)\: 4177920 
      Virtual hardware 10 (vSphere 5.5)\: 1035264 
      Virtual hardware 9 (vSphere 5.1)\: 1035264 
      Virtual hardware 8 (vSphere 5.0)\:  1035264

When running on Unix, you cannot determine the type of shell to be used (sh, bash, ksh, csh, etc), so make sure to include the shell in your command if you want to perform operations such as file redirection.  
Example\: sh -c "ls -lha /etc > /tmp/myfile".

When running on Windows, this command  prepends "cmd.exe /C" or "command.exe /C" to the command you specify, so there is no need to pass this information to the operation.

Inputs\:
    command - The command to execute.
    arguments - Any arguments needed for the command.
    environment - Specifies environment variables/values that need to be defined when running the command.
    path - The path to the commands executable.
    cmd_timeout - Timeout in milliseconds before the command is considered as having failed when "returnImmediately" is false.
Default value\: 100000 (100 seconds).
    returnImmediately - If "true", the operation executes the command and returns a result immediately.  It does not wait for the command to finish.
Valid values\: true, false.
Default value\: false.

    STDOUT - The standard output of the command.

    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Sets the number of CPUs for a virtual machine.  Virtual machine cannot be in a suspended power state.  CPU hot plug is supported if enabled for the virtual machine.

Inputs\:
   host - VMWare host hostname or IP.
   user - VMWare username.
   password - VMWare user's password.
   port - Port to connect on.
   protocol - Connection protocol. Valid values\: http, https.
   closeSession - Close the internally kept VMWare Infrastructure API session at completion of operation. Valid values\:true, false.
   async - Asynchronously perform the task. Valid values\: true, false.
   taskTimeOut - Time to wait before the operation is considered to have failed (seconds).
   virtualMachine - Primary Virtual Machine identifier. Inventorypath (Datacenter/vm/Folder/MyVM), Name of VM, IP (IPv4 or IPv6 depending upon ESX version), hostname (full), UUID, or the VM id (vm-123,123).
   vmIdentifierType - Virtual machine identifier type. Valid values\:inventorypath, name, ip, hostname, uuid, vmid.
   vmDatacenter - Virtual machine's datacenter.
   vmCpuCount - New number of CPUs for the virtual machine.

Responses\:
   success - If async is true the task was successfuly queued.  If async is false the CPU count for the virtual machine was successfully set.
   failure - Something went wrong.  See returnResult for details.

Returns\:
   returnResult - Task result or operation result.

Notes\:
   1. Inventory Path Formatting\: If host is an ESX server inventory path will be\: ha-datacenter/vm/ .  If host is a vCenter the inventory path will be\: /vm// . The / part of the path is based on the "Virtual Machines & Templates" view in the vCenter client. The inventory path is case sensitive.
   2. CPU limits\: The maximum value for 'vmCpuCount' is based on the virtual hardware version of the virtual machine. Limits are as follows\:
       Virtual hardware 11 (vSphere 6.0)\: 128
       Virtual hardware 10 (vSphere 5.5)\: 64
       Virtual hardware 9 (vSphere 5.1)\: 64
       Virtual hardware 8 (vSphere 5.0)\: 32
       Virtual hardware 7 (vSphere 4)\: 8
       Virtual hardware 4 (ESX 3.x)\: 4
       Virtual hardware 3 (ESX 2.5)\: 2
       For more details regarding configuration maximums and virtual machine compatibility settings see http\://pubs.vmware.com/vsphere-60/index.jsp\#com.vmware.vsphere.vm_admin.doc/GUID-789C3913-1053-4850-A0F0-E29C3D32B6DA.html
   3. The number of CPUs specified in the 'vmCpuCount' must not exceed the number of CPUs available on the ESX/ESXi host on which the Virtual Machine will run. When the specified value is greater than the number of CPUs available and below the configuration maximums the number of CPUs will be set to that value for the specified virtual machine however the virtual machine will not be usable.
